SCOPE AND LIMITATIONS
System Scope
TaskFlow focuses on portfolio and workload orchestration collaboration, forensic visibility, notification handling, authentication, and dashboard aggregation. Each controller delegates to the service layer.

System Limitations
The platform is scoped for 100 to 10,000 concurrent users within a single region architecture. Beyond that scale a different deployment topology and service decomposition are required. Financial systems and CRM modules are intentionally excluded to maintain focus on core transaction safety.

Deployment and Latency Assumptions
Performance targets assume a low latency network environment. Rate limits protect throughput and cached KPI values may be slightly stale by design to preserve responsiveness.

CONCEPTUAL AND LOGICAL ARCHITECTURE
Relational Backbone and Entity Hierarchy
The data model uses a three tier cascade: identity containers and operational work units. Users and roles establish an authorization perimeter, projects act as containers, and tasks are the primary operational entities. Dependent entities include comments attachments and activity logs where ledger entries are treated as immutable append only records.

BUSINESS RULES
1. A Project can contain many Tasks. Each Task belongs to exactly one Project.
2. A Task can have many Comments and many Attachments. Each Comment and each Attachment belongs to exactly one Task.
3. A User or Employee can handle many Tasks. Each Task is assigned to one responsible User or Employee at a time.
4. Every significant task action creates one Activity record. Each Activity record is linked to exactly one Task and one User.

CONCLUSION
TaskFlow demonstrates that rigorous application of database design principles combined with disciplined architectural practices produces a task management platform that is robust, performant and maintainable. The system balances normalized data models with index driven query optimization and caching to deliver accurate results with interactive latency.

